title: For Sale:  WINCHESTER MODEL 12 12-Ga -- w/ 2 SOLID RIB BBLS...30 FULL/26 CYL...Mfd 1951
postcontent: Here's a versatile shotgun! This is a Winchester Model 12 pump that comes with two different complete front ends. Both barrels feature factory solid ribs. One barrel measures 30" in length and is marked for Full choke, while the other barrel measures 26" and is marked for Cylinder bore choke. Both barrels are serial numbered to match the receiver. The 30" barrel is likely original to the gun, while the 26" barrel is certainly of earlier production, marked "Model 1912". Each barrel features two sight beads. The mid bead has been added to the 26" barrel as has the "glow worm" front sight on the 30" barrel. The gun has been refinished in the past but it was a very decent job and the gun looks quite nice. There is no rust or pitting and the finish rates about 98% with a few marks to the front of the receiver from careless assembly. The stocks are sound and free of cracks or chips. There are a few handling marks and the varnish on the buttstock is a little heavy and uneven. LOP measures 14" over the red rubber Winchester marked replacement buttpad. Mechanically, this shotgun appears to be in good working order and both barrels snug down nicely to the frame. The bores are in good shape too and are free of pitting or problems. This should make a handy dual-purpose shotgun for someone who can appreciate the shooting qualities that defined the classic Winchester Model 12

In the late nineties, the South African police issued a requirement for a compact, concealable pistol chambered for 9x19 ammunition. In 1997, the contract for a new police pistol went to the Republic Arms Company, which had developed the RAP-401 pistol, a relatively compact sidearm suitable for concealed carry. Later on, Republic Arms also produced a .40 calibre version of the same pistol, intended for export. This was designated RAP-440. It seems that RAP pistols were influenced by the Spanish Astra A-75. RAP pistols are favored for their reliability and mild recoil; on the other hand, these pistols are somewhat heavy for their pocket size.
The RAP-401 is a short-recoil operated, locked-breech pistol of all-steel construction. It uses a modified Browning type locking system, as the barrel engages the slide with a single lug that enters the ejection window. Unlocking is controlled by a cam-shaped lug below the barrel. The trigger is double-action, with an exposed hammer and frame-mounted safety, which also doubles as a decocker. Sights are fixed. Magazines are single-stack; the magazine release button is located at the base of the trigger-guard.

As you can see in the pictures, it is in great shape and inexpensive for the quality of it! It is made by Tanfoglio of Italy.

I will only sell to people with permit to purchase or permit to carry.

For more info text me or call me at six12 22four 5245

Here's more info on the gun gathered from the internet:

These were Italian made single action .380 pistols, also made in .32 ACP. They are all steel, well made, very reliable and seem to feed nearly every type of .380 ammo with no problems, and are pretty accurate for their type. I own 2 of them, both Tanfoglios, both imported by EXCAM probably in the 1980's. 

Here's the manual for all of these pistols...

http://www.eaacorp.com/Manuals/ea380-manual.pdf

There were variations of these pistols, but all are the same basic design and they are all good guns. They sort of look like the old Beretta M.70, but are not similar internally. They have a slide lock safety, a mag safety and a firing pin block safety, which I engage in order to safely lower the hammer manually on a loaded chamber. I carry one of mine loaded with Remington Golden Sabers, which feed like glass in this pistol. I have ordered flat wood grips from EAA to replace the 1980's "thumbrest" grips that I find very uncomfortable to carry and to shoot. 

Mags and at least some parts are available from EAA and from Numrich, but you probably won't need any.
In my experience, they work best with a light lube on the rails and a little in the works... I also recommend a thorough cleaning if you find one - they are pretty old and like most low priced guns, did not get a lot of respect/cleaning/attention...a little maintenance makes a lot of difference.

They were very inexpensive pistols when new, and still can be a good choice for a rugged, reliable carry or home defense pistol for not much money.

title: For Sale:  LWRC -- M6.8-A2 6.8 SPC II SIX8 Zeiss Victory
postcontent:
The SIX8™ weapons are short-stroke, gas-piston operated rifles chambered in the 6.8x43mm SPC cartridge. This cartridge was developed as part of the Enhanced Rifle Cartridge Program in which U.S. Special Operations soldiers, as well as armorers and other technicians from the U.S. Army Marksmanship Unit, played a major role. Its primary purpose was to address the deficiencies in terminal performance seen with the 5.56x45mm NATO cartridge, while allowing the soldier to carry the same number of rounds with minimal weight penalty. It succeeds in doing so because it uses a heavier bullet with excellent accuracy, which delivers more energy across all effective ranges.

Until now, a major drawback of using the 6.8 cartridge in an M4 style weapon has been the lack of reliable magazines. So, when we designed the SIX8™ family of weapons, we started with the magazine. Partnering with Magpul®, the leader in polymer magazine engineering, we designed the first polymer 6.8 magazine. Building upon the magazine, we designed the SIX8™ platform for maximum reliability and improved ergonomics. The upper and lower receivers are designed to accommodate the slightly larger polymer magazine and to perfect the feed geometry for the 6.8 cartridge. In addition, we have prompted Federal Ammunition to develop new lines of affordably priced, high performance 6.8 ammunition for commercial, law enforcement and military applications.

As with the IC family, the weapons in the new SIX8™ family are fully ambidextrous and equally suited to right- or left-handed operators. The SIX8™ rifles are based on the familiar Stoner M4/AR15/M16 architecture, but they have been optimized specifically for use with the 6.8 cartridge.

The new SIX8™ family combines the ultimate in ergonomic user-friendly rifles with the outstanding mid-range 6.8 cartridge.

title: For Sale:  LWRC -- M6.8-A2 6.8 SPC II SIX8 Zeiss Victory
postcontent:
The SIX8™ weapons are short-stroke, gas-piston operated rifles chambered in the 6.8x43mm SPC cartridge. This cartridge was developed as part of the Enhanced Rifle Cartridge Program in which U.S. Special Operations soldiers, as well as armorers and other technicians from the U.S. Army Marksmanship Unit, played a major role. Its primary purpose was to address the deficiencies in terminal performance seen with the 5.56x45mm NATO cartridge, while allowing the soldier to carry the same number of rounds with minimal weight penalty. It succeeds in doing so because it uses a heavier bullet with excellent accuracy, which delivers more energy across all effective ranges.

Until now, a major drawback of using the 6.8 cartridge in an M4 style weapon has been the lack of reliable magazines. So, when we designed the SIX8™ family of weapons, we started with the magazine. Partnering with Magpul®, the leader in polymer magazine engineering, we designed the first polymer 6.8 magazine. Building upon the magazine, we designed the SIX8™ platform for maximum reliability and improved ergonomics. The upper and lower receivers are designed to accommodate the slightly larger polymer magazine and to perfect the feed geometry for the 6.8 cartridge. In addition, we have prompted Federal Ammunition to develop new lines of affordably priced, high performance 6.8 ammunition for commercial, law enforcement and military applications.

As with the IC family, the weapons in the new SIX8™ family are fully ambidextrous and equally suited to right- or left-handed operators. The SIX8™ rifles are based on the familiar Stoner M4/AR15/M16 architecture, but they have been optimized specifically for use with the 6.8 cartridge.

The new SIX8™ family combines the ultimate in ergonomic user-friendly rifles with the outstanding mid-range 6.8 cartridge.

Caliber: 6.8mm SPC

Barrel Length: 16.1"

Weight (unloaded): 7.3lbs (16.1" barrel)

Length (overall): 31.25" - 34" (16.1" barrel)

Rate of Fire: Semi Auto or Select Fire 700 rpm (+/- 100rpm)

Rifling: 1/10" RH

Stock/Pistol Grip: LWRCI/Magpul MOE

Sights: LWRCI Folding BUIS Front and Rear

postcontent:
One owner family Kawasaki KZ750 LTD

Purchased new in 1981 by my uncle who loved bikes but had a bad heart and couldn't ride much. It has just over 4,900 original miles on it. It's always been stored inside; never a night outside. When I inherited the bike in 2009, I went through getting it tuned up and got it on the road for a while until the rear brake caliper cylinder seal blew. I drained the gas then and it's been parked in my garage since and haven't gotten around to replacing/rebuilding the brake caliper yet and finally just decided that it's better now, to sell it to someone with more time and know-how than I have. 

I just got it out of the garage to take a few pictures and see the battery is dead from sitting, so at minimum, it will need a new battery, tune up and the brakes gone through. 

It's completely original/stock and will make a great project and/or restoration bike. It is filthy and needs a really good cleaning. Cosmetically there is surface rust in places (exhaust pipes, etc) from sitting but very solid overall. This is the more desirable KZ750, being a 4 cylinder with quad carbs. It's a 33 year old bike and therefore sold AS IS. 

Clean title in hand. 

First $750, picked up in Hartford. 

The only trades I'd consider would be firearms, otherwise just cash.

Thanks, Rob
